{
  "texts": [
    "The measure of deviation is based on the Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence, which is a concept in information theory that measures how one probability distribution diverges from a reference probability distribution.",
    "For completeness, the KL divergence of distribution Q from P is where P(i) and Q(i) are the probabilities of the i th event occurring to distributions P and Q, respectively.",
    "In this context, P represents the probability distribution of events according to the original policy, while Q represents the probability of the same events according to the revised policy after the parameter updates.",
    "By constraining the amount of divergence, PPO maintains a balance between exploring new strategies and exploiting the knowledge contained in the original model, thus ensuring stability and reliability in model training.",
    "Measuring deviation helps to prevent the model from overfitting to the rewards from RLHF and ensures that the updates to the policy are not too drastic, which could lead to unstable learning behavior."
  ]
}